4620000 -1597000 12110000 15179000 100000000 50000000 4100000 4100000 0 0 11500000 5300000 177507000 183978000 2000000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">16. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The Company is</font><font style="display: inline;"> currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs &amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of</font><font style="display: inline;"> the period from 2006 to 2010. </font><font style="display: inline;">In October 2013, CBP issued the final audit report. In that report CBP projects that unpaid duties totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$12.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million are due for the period under review and recommends</font><font style="display: inline;"> collection of the duties due. Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is consider</font><font style="display: inline;">ably less than the projection. </font><font style="display: inline;">Additi</font><font style="display: inline;">onally, on December 12, 2014, Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> made an offer to settle CBP&#x2019;s potential cl</font><font style="display: inline;">aims and tendered </font><font style="display: inline;">$3.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million.</font><font style="display: inline;"> At this time, it is not possible to determine how long </font><font style="display: inline;">it will take CBP to evaluate the</font><font style="display: inline;"> offer or to predict whet</font><font style="display: inline;">her the offer will be accepted.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Likewise, if a settlement cannot be reached, it is not possible to predict with any certainty whether CBP will seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any unpaid duties, but such an assertion is a possibility.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) has audited the </font><font style="display: inline;">C</font><font style="display: inline;">ompany&#x2019;s records regarding imports and exports during the period f</font><font style="display: inline;">rom January 2006 to July 2011. </font><font style="display: inline;">There were two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods an</font><font style="display: inline;">d the second for raw materials.</font><font style="display: inline;"> The first phase was completed and no major discre</font><font style="display: inline;">pancies were noted by the SAT. </font><font style="display: inline;">On January 9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT issued a tax assessment (taxes and penalties) of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;">280.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million pesos (approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$22.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million) based on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw mate</font><font style="display: inline;">rials during the audit period. Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> believe</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> that the proposed penalty amount is unfounded and without merit. W</font><font style="display: inline;">ith the help of local counsel Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> filed an appeal by t</font><font style="display: inline;">he deadline of March 15, 2013. Crocs has</font><font style="display: inline;"> argued that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially less </font><font style="display: inline;">than that proposed by the SAT. </font><font style="display: inline;">In connection with the appea</font><font style="display: inline;">l, the SAT required Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> to post an appeal surety bond in the amount of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;">321.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million pesos (approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$26.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million), which amount reflects estimated additional </font><font style="display: inline;">penalties and interest if the Company is not successful on its appeal. </font><font style="display: inline;">This amount will be adjusted on an annual basis. On November 27, 2014, the Superior Chamber of the Federal Tax Court ruled in favor of Crocs and annulled the tax assessment </font><font style="display: inline;">and the corresponding penalty. </font><font style="display: inline;">The SAT filed its appeal of the decision in Crocs&#x2019; favor on February 25, 2015. On June 24, 2015, the Circuit Court rejected SAT&#xB4;s appeal, and thus, confirmed the favorable decision issued to C</font><font style="display: inline;">rocs by the Federal Tax Court. </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs has not yet been served with the final written opinion but expects to receive the same within the</font><font style="display: inline;"> next two months. </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs will not know if the SAT ha</font><font style="display: inline;">s a right of appeal until then.</font><font style="display: inline;"> It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter or reasonably estimate any potential loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Crocs is currently subject to an audit by the Brazilian Federal Tax Authorities related to imports of footwear</font><font style="display: inline;"> from China between 2010 and 2014. </font><font style="display: inline;">On January 13, 2015 Crocs was notified about the issuance of assessments totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$5.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million for the period</font><font style="display: inline;"> January 2010 through May 2011.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Crocs has disputed these assessments and as</font><font style="display: inline;">serted defenses to the claims. </font><font style="display: inline;">On February 25, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;"> Crocs received additional assessments totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$11.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million related to the </font><font style="display: inline;">remainder of the audit period. </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs has also disputed these assessments and asser</font><font style="display: inline;">ted defenses to these claims. </font><font style="display: inline;">It is anticipated that this matter will take up t</font><font style="display: inline;">o several years to be resolved.</font><font style="display: inline;"> It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August 8, 2014, a purported class action lawsuit was filed in Califo</font><font style="display: inline;">rnia State Court against a Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">subsidiary, Crocs Retail, LLC (</font><font style="display: inline;">Zaydenberg v. Crocs Retail, LLC, Case No. BC554214). The lawsuit alleged various employment law violations related to overtime, meal and break periods, minimum wage, timely payment of wages, wage statements, payroll</font><font style="display: inline;"> records and business expenses. Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> filed an answer on February 6, 2015, denying the allegations a</font><font style="display: inline;">nd asserting several defenses. </font><font style="display: inline;">On June 3, 2015, a second purported class action l</font><font style="display: inline;">awsuit was filed in California State C</font><font style="display: inline;">ourt against Crocs Retail, LLC (Christopher S. Duree and Richard Morely v. Crocs, Inc., Case No. BC583875), making substantially the same allegations as in the Zaydenberg lawsuit. The parties attended a mediation on June 26, 2015, and reached a preliminary settlement for both lawsuits. The parties are now petitioning the</font><font style="display: inline;"> State</font><font style="display: inline;"> Court for approval of the settlement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of June 30, 2015, Crocs estimates that the ultimate resolution of these litigation matters and other disputes could result in a loss that is reasonably possible between </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">11.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in aggregate, </font><font style="display: inline;">of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$5.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million </font><font style="display: inline;">has been accrued.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Although Crocs is</font><font style="display: inline;"> subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs is</font><font style="display: inline;"> not party to any other p</font><font style="display: inline;">ending legal proceedings that Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;"> believe</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> would reasonably have a material adverse impact on </font><font style="display: inline;">its</font><font style="display: inline;"> business, financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We rent space for our retail stores, offices, warehouses, vehicles, and equipment under operating leases expiring at various dates through 2033. Certain leases contain rent escalation clauses (step rents) that require additional rental amounts in the later years of the term. Rent expense for leases with step rents or rent holidays is recognized on a straight-line basis over the lease term beginning on the lease inception date. Deferred rent is included in the </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed consolidated</font><font style="display: inline;"> balance sheets in &#x2018;Accrued expenses and other current liabilities</font><font style="display: inline;">.&#x2019;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">BANK BORROWINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On September 25, 2009, we entered into a Revolving Credit and Security Agreement (the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;) with the lenders named therein and PNC Bank, National Association ("PNC"), as a lender and administrative agent for the lenders. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On April 2, 2015</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">we entered into the Sixth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Ag</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">reement (the &#x201C;Sixth Amendment&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> pursuant to which certain terms of the Credit Agreement were </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">amended. The </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Sixth Amendment</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> primarily amended certain definitions of the</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> financial covenants to b</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e more favorable to us including (i) setting the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through December 31, 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.15</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through March 31, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.25</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for each quarter thereafter, (ii)&nbsp;setting the Leverage Ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">4.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through March 31, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">3.75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for each quarter thereafter and&nbsp;(iii) reducing our global cash requirement from </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$100</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The Credit Agreement enables us to borrow up </font><font style="display: inline;">to </font><font style="display: inline;">$100.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, with the abilit</font><font style="display: inline;">y to increase commitments </font><font style="display: inline;">to </font><font style="display: inline;">$125.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> subject to certain conditions, and is currently set </font><font style="display: inline;">to mature in </font><font style="display: inline;">December 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity </font><font style="display: inline;">interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of our assets including all receivables, equipment, general intangibles, inventory, investment property, subsidiary stock and intellectual property. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement bear interest at a variable rate</font><font style="display: inline;">. For domestic rate loans, the interest rate is equal to the highest of (i) the daily federal funds open rate as quoted by ICAP North America, Inc. plus </font><font style="display: inline;">0.5%</font><font style="display: inline;">, (ii) PNC's prime rate and (iii) a daily LIBOR rate plus </font><font style="display: inline;">1.0%</font><font style="display: inline;">, in each case there is an additional margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">0.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">1.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. For LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">1.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">2.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. The Credit Agreement requires monthly interest payments with respect to domestic rate loans and at the end of each interest period with respect to LIBOR rate loans. The Credit Agreement further provides for a limit on the issuance of letters of credit to a maximum </font><font style="display: inline;">of </font><font style="display: inline;">$20.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">. The Credit Agreement contains provisions requiring us to maintain compliance with certain restrictive and financial covenants. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, </font><font style="display: inline;">201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the Credit Agreement. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, </font><font style="display: inline;">201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had outstanding letters of </font><font style="display: inline;">credit of </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">1.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$1.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of the Credit Agreement</font><font style="display: inline;">. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015, we were in compliance with all restrictive financial and other covenants under the Credit Agreement.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Long-T</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">erm Bank Borrowings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On December 10, 2012, we entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;Master IPA&#x201D;) with PNC in which PNC financed the Company&#x2019;s recent implementation of a new enterprise resource planning (&#x201C;ERP&#x201D;) system, which began in October 2012 and was substantially completed in early 2015. The terms of each note payable, under the Master IPA, consist of a fixed interest rate and payment terms based on the amount borrowed and the timing of activity throughout the implementation of the ERP system. The Master IPA is subject to cross-default, cross-termination, and is co-terminous with the Credit Agreement. We are in compliance with the covenants under the Credit Agreement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, </font><font style="display: inline;">201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had </font><font style="display: inline;">$9.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$11.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, of</font><font style="display: inline;"> debt outstanding under </font><font style="display: inline;">five</font><font style="display: inline;"> separate notes payable, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">of which </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$5.</font><font style="display: inline;">3</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> million </font><font style="display: inline;">represent</font><font style="display: inline;">s &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">current installments</font><font style="display: inline;"> for both periods</font><font style="display: inline;">. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;">, the notes bear interest rates ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.45%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.79%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">and maturities ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2016</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. As this debt arrangement relates solely to the construction and implementation of an ERP system for use by the entity, interest expense </font><font style="display: inline;">was</font><font style="display: inline;"> capitalized to the condensed consolidated balance sheets until the assets </font><font style="display: inline;">were placed into service on January 1, 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;">During the </font><font style="display: inline;">six months</font><font style="display: inline;"> ended </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5, </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> interest was capitalized. During the three and six months ended June 30,</font><font style="display: inline;"> 201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;">, we capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million </font><font style="display: inline;">and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million </font><font style="display: inline;">in interest expense related to this debt arrangement to the condensed consolidated balance sheets. Interest rates and payment terms are subject to changes as further financing occurs under the Master IPA.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The components of our consolidated debt and capital lease obligations are as follows:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">have </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">enter</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> into foreign currency exchange forward contract</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and currency swap derivative instruments </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreig</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n currency exchange rates. We do not designate these</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">recognized in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">gain (loss)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, net&#x2019; in our </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">condensed consolidated statements of operations. For purposes of the cash flow statement, we classify</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">items, generally with</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">in &#x2018;Cash provided by operating activities</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.&#x2019;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign cur</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">rency exchange contracts as of June 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> are denominated in their U.S. D</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of our exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks.</font> </p> <p </div> </div> 3033000 3067000 3000000 0.26 0.19 0.04 0.11 0.25 0.19 0.04 0.11 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to comm</font><font style="display: inline;">on stockholders by the weighted </font><font style="display: inline;">average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in a</font><font style="display: inline;">ny form. Our</font><font style="display: inline;"> Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;"> issued in 2014</font><font style="display: inline;"> represents participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of our non-vested restricted stock </font><font style="display: inline;">and restricted stock unit </font><font style="display: inline;">awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in our earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above</font><font style="display: inline;">. This method</font><font style="display: inline;"> assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 1</font><font style="display: inline;">2</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. EARNINGS PER SHARE</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table illustrates the basic and diluted </font><font style="display: inline;">EPS</font><font style="display: inline;"> computations for the </font><font style="display: inline;">three and six months end</font><font style="display: inline;">ed </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">5 and 2014</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:01.96%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt style="width:01.96%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;"> <p FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">A</font><font style="display: inline;">s of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, our Level 1 assets subject to fair value measurements Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of our non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorded. During </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">both </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">the three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and six</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> months ended June 30, 2015 and 2014, we recorded $2.1 million and $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">3.2 million, respectively, in</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> impairment charge</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s associated with the Company&#x2019;s retail locations</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 78126000 4170000 4931000 62591000 5798000 636000 91415000 4170000 4959000 76883000 5053000 350000 18750000 9957000 12232000 14153000 16608000 18329000 175130000 4170000 6702000 157615000 5945000 698000 181444000 4170000 6594000 165277000 5053000 350000 97004000 1771000 95024000 147000 62000 90029000 1635000 88394000 -2988000 -220000 277000 -217000 10892000 180000 -5208000 -3370000 -4343000 1380000 2044000 2227000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4. INCOME TAXES</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">During the three months</font><font style="display: inline;"> ended June 30, 2015, the Company recognized income tax expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million on pre-tax income of </font><font style="display: inline;">$16.0 million</font><font style="display: inline;">, representing an effective income tax rate of </font><font style="display: inline;">16.</font><font style="display: inline;">0</font><font style="display: inline;">%</font><font style="display: inline;">. For</font><font style="display: inline;"> the same period in 2014, the Company recognized income tax expense of $18.7 million on pre-tax income of $42.0 million, representing an effective tax rate of </font><font style="display: inline;">44.6%</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp;&nbsp;During the six months ended June 30, 2015, the Company recognized income tax expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.9</font><font style="display: inline;"> million on pre-tax income </font><font style="display: inline;">of $13.9</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, representing an effective income tax rate </font><font style="display: inline;">of </font><font style="display: inline;">20.6%</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font><font style="display: inline;"> For the same period in 2014, the Company recognized income tax expense of $24.1 million on pre-tax income of $56.5 million, representing an effective tax rate of </font><font style="display: inline;">42.6%</font><font style="display: inline;">.&nbsp; </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The decrease in effective tax rate, compared to the same period in 2014, is primarily due to the recognition of unrecognized tax benefits in connection with various favorable audit settlements</font><font style="display: inline;"> in foreign jurisdictions</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font><font style="display: inline;"> The Company&#x2019;s effective income tax rate, for all periods presented, differs from the federal U.S. statutory rate due to differences in income tax rates between U.S. and foreign jurisdictions as well as tax amounts recognized discretely during the quarter. The Company had unrecognized tax </font><font style="display: inline;">benefits of </font><font style="display: inline;">$4.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$8.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million at June 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, respectively.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 23174000 13371000 9332000 15443000 24076000 18719000 2857000 2562000 34015000 43383000 94840000 80201000 -3130000 10025000 30769000 15862000 7760000 18926000 563000 3347000 788000 -531000 3839000 -804000 1314000 912000 1256000 1356000 333000 307000 99381000 92563000 200000 100000 319000 128000 479000 260000 204000 479000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">3</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:15.16%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 1609000 4769000 2663000 6381000 3691000 0.0263 11700000 0 131131000 -50616000 -31065000 -9141000 -16979000 -3051000 32401000 23277000 11001000 13426000 25896000 19523000 3711000 9690000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In April 2015, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Sta</font><font style="display: inline;">ndards Update ("ASU") 2015-03: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. This ASU requires retrospective adoption and will be effective for us beginning in our first quarter of 2016. Early adoption is permitted. We do not expect that this pronouncement will have a material impact on our </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;">consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On June 19, 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. We do not expect that this pronouncement will have a material impact on our </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;">consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration </font><font style="display: inline;">to which</font><font style="display: inline;"> the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; In applying the revenue model to contracts within its scope, an entity:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Identifies the contract(s) with a customer (Step 1)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Identifies the performance obligations in the contract (Step 2)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Determines the transaction price (Step 3)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Allocates the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract (Step 4)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Recognizes revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation (Step 5)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The ASU applies to all contracts with customers except those that are within the scope of other topics in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Certain of the ASU&#x2019;s provisions also apply to transfers of nonfinancial assets, including in-substance nonfinancial assets that are not an output of an entity&#x2019;s ordinary activities (e.g., sales of property, plant, and equipment, real estate or intangible assets). Existing accounting guidance applicable to these transfers has been amended or superseded. Compared with current GAAP, the ASU also requires significantly expanded disclosures about revenue recognition. </font><font style="display: inline;">On July 9, 2015, the FASB deferred the effective date to reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2017. </font><font style="display: inline;">Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. We are currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on our </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;">consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In July 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;">the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11:</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. Under existing standards, the market amount requires consideration of replacement cost, net realizable value (&#x201C;NRV&#x201D;), and NRV less an approximately normal profit margin. The new ASU replaces market with NRV, defined as estimated selling prices in the ordinary course of business, less reasonably predictable costs of completion, disposal and transportation. This eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or NRV less an approximately normal profit margin </font><font style="display: inline;">when measuring inventory. T</font><font style="display: inline;">his standard is effective prospectively beginning January 1, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently assessing this ASU&#x2019;s impacts on </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2019; consolidated results of operations and financial condition.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after June 30, 2015 are not expected to have a material impact on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 4 3 58733000 -8345000 30000 -72782000 139830000 38357000 81908000 19565000 41911000 -4589000 15000 -38224000 84709000 24920000 47763000 12026000 13987000 -12294000 -83808000 110089000 37149000 58597000 14343000 16349000 -6890000 -45899000 69138000 21771000 41262000 6105000 9684000 7261000 8005000 5927000 55649000 28110000 49858000 25106000 64886000 35128000 57745000 30974000 447000 243000 118000 59000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; BASIS OF PRESENTATION</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Organization</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. and its subsidiaries (collectively the &#x201C;Company,&#x201D; &#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;our&#x201D; or &#x201C;us&#x201D;) are engaged in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing and distribution of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Basis of Presentation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. The condensed consolidated balance sheet as of December 31, 2014 was derived from the Company&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2014 (the &#x201C;2014 Form 10-K&#x201D;) but does not contain all information required for complete financial statements. The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements and these notes thereto should be read in conjunction with the 2014 Form 10-K. In the opinion of management, these </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed consolidated </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair statement of the results for the interim periods presented. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Reclassifications</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Certain prior period amounts on the condensed consolidated financial statements have been reclassified to conform to current period presentation. We segregated certain restructuring charges recorded to selling, gen</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">eral and administrative expense</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> on the condensed consolidated statements of operations during the three and six months ended June 30, 2014 to the restructuring charges line item. These reclassifications had no effect on income from operations, current l</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">iabilities or cash used in</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> operating activities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:inherit;color:#000000;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In April 2015, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Sta</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ndards Update ("ASU") 2015-03: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. This ASU requires retrospective adoption and will be effective for us beginning in our first quarter of 2016. Early adoption is permitted. We do not expect that this pronouncement will have a material impact on our </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">On June 19, 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. We do not expect that this pronouncement will have a material impact on our </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration </font><font style="display: inline;">to which</font><font style="display: inline;"> the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; In applying the revenue model to contracts within its scope, an entity:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Identifies the contract(s) with a customer (Step 1)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Identifies the performance obligations in the contract (Step 2)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Determines the transaction price (Step 3)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Allocates the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract (Step 4)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -4.5pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Recognizes revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation (Step 5)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The ASU applies to all contracts with customers except those that are within the scope of other topics in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Certain of the ASU&#x2019;s provisions also apply to transfers of nonfinancial assets, including in-substance nonfinancial assets that are not an output of an entity&#x2019;s ordinary activities (e.g., sales of property, plant, and equipment, real estate or intangible assets). Existing accounting guidance applicable to these transfers has been amended or superseded. Compared with current GAAP, the ASU also requires significantly expanded disclosures about revenue recognition. </font><font style="display: inline;">On July 9, 2015, the FASB deferred the effective date to reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2017. </font><font style="display: inline;">Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. We are currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on our </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;">consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In July 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;">the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11:</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. Under existing standards, the market amount requires consideration of replacement cost, net realizable value (&#x201C;NRV&#x201D;), and NRV less an approximately normal profit margin. The new ASU replaces market with NRV, defined as estimated selling prices in the ordinary course of business, less reasonably predictable costs of completion, disposal and transportation. This eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or NRV less an approximately normal profit margin </font><font style="display: inline;">when measuring inventory. T</font><font style="display: inline;">his standard is effective prospectively beginning January 1, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently assessing this ASU&#x2019;s impacts on </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2019; consolidated results of operations and financial condition.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after June 30, 2015 are not expected to have a material impact on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> These reclassifications had no effect on income from operations, current l</font><font style="display: inline;">iabilities or cash used in</font><font style="display: inline;"> operating activities.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 1209000 959000 182220000 43000 68288000 59501000 3867000 6220000 202300000 123800000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">6</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. RESTRUCTURING ACTIVITIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restructuring</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">July 21, 2014, we announced strategic plans for long-term improvement and growth of the business. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">These plans comprise</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> four key initiatives including</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> (1) streamlining the global product and marketing portfolio, (2) reducing direct investment in smaller geographic markets, (3) creating a more efficient organizational structure </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">by</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> reducing excess overhead </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">and enhancing</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> the decision making process, and (4) closing or converting </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">approximately </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">75</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">100</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> retail locations</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;"> around the world. The initial effects of these plans were incurred in 2014 and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">are continuing throughout 2015. W</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">e</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> recorded restructuring charges </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">2.8</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">16</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> stores, a</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">s identified in the initial restructuring plan, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">during the three </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">and six month periods ended June 30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">respectively</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During 2015, we currently estimate restructuring costs related to store closures and changes in organizational structure of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$10</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$15</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, but </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">we </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">can make no assurance that actual costs will not differ, as our restructuring plans are not yet complete.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes our restructuring activity during the three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and six </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">June 30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, 2015 and 2014:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <tr> <td valign="bottom" style="width:34.54%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9
